Ask HN: What happens after ChatGPT gets access to real world APIs?
text:
I was just playing with the idea of ChatGPT replacing the backend of Alexa, Siri etc and I found some very dystopian scenarios.

Do APIs need a more restrictive permissions model? How do we protect the real world from hallucinating technologies that can interact with our physical infrastructure?

title: Post-Mortem Stewardship
text:
What do you think happens to open source libraries whose maintainers shuffle from the mortal coil?

They never set a plan to hand over the keys, so are the libraries set in stone and simply need to be forked, or is there a way to carry on the mantle?

title: AC Power Filters and Electromagnetic Compliance: A View from the Field (2017)
Aerospike community edition is cripleware
text:
It doesn't support IPv6 and the open source server license is a commercial license.

These commercial-crippled products (and also AGPL banned at most businesses including Google) are footgun sniping themselves. If a software company wants customers to use their stuff, then they have to reduce friction. Locking up features or imposing a business-unfriendly license are a hard pass.

Either be open source or don't. Pretending to be open source is worse than remaining closed source.

https://aerospike.com/products/features-and-editions/
